def get_dataset():
    """Creates and returns the complete dataset."""
    Data_images_ = glob.glob("/content/Image-Medica/Dataset/Images/*")
    Data_labels_ = glob.glob("/content/Image-Medica/Dataset/GT/*")
    extract_number = lambda x: int(x.split('/')[-1].split('_c')[-1].split('.')[0])
    Data_images = sorted(Data_images_, key=extract_number)
    Data_labels = sorted(Data_labels_, key=extract_number)
    return Data_images, Data_labels

class Split_Data():
    def __init__(self, data, label, train_size, validate_size, test_size, shuffle=True, random_state = 123):
        self.data = data
        self.label = label
        self.train_size = train_size
        self.validate_size = validate_size
        self.test_size = test_size
        self.random_state = random_state
        self.shuffle = shuffle

    def split(self, n):
        np.random.seed(self.random_state)
        sample = np.arange(n)
        if self.shuffle:
            np.random.shuffle(sample)
        train, validate, test = np.split(sample, [int(self.train_size*n), int((self.train_size + self.validate_size)*n)]) # [0, 0.6] U [0.6, 0.8] U [0.8, 1] => [0.6, 0.8]
        return train, validate, test

    def DataForLoop(self, data_):
        return [self.data[i] for i in data_]

    def LabelForLoop(self, data_):
        return [self.label[i] for i in data_]

    def train_val_test(self):
        sum_prop_split = round( 1- (self.train_size + self.validate_size + self.test_size), 2)
        if sum_prop_split != 0.00: # This will avoid any floating data
            raise RuntimeError('The sum of train_size, validate_size, and test_size needs to be 1.')
        if len(self.data) == len(self.label):
            n = len(self.data)
        else:
            raise RuntimeError('The length of the data and label are not the same.')
        train, val, test = self.split(n = n)
        data_train = self.DataForLoop(train)
        data_val =  self.DataForLoop(val)
        data_test =  self.DataForLoop(test)
        labels_train =  self.LabelForLoop(train)
        labels_val =  self.LabelForLoop(val)
        labels_test =  self.LabelForLoop(test)
        return data_train, data_val, data_test, labels_train, labels_val, labels_test

class _WrappedDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, paths_img: Union[str, Path], paths_labels: Union[str, Path],
                 transform_img: Optional[Callable] = None,  transform_label: Optional[Callable] = None,
                 random_state: int = 123, mode_color_img = 'RGB', mode_color_label = 'L'):
        self.paths_img = paths_img
        self.paths_labels = paths_labels
        self.transform_img = transform_img
        self.transform_label = transform_label
        self.random_state = random_state
        self.mode_color_img = mode_color_img
        self.mode_color_label = mode_color_label

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.paths_img)

    def __getitem__(self, index):
        path_img = self.paths_img[index]
        path_labels = self.paths_labels[index]
        image = Image.open(path_img).convert(self.mode_color_img)
        label = Image.open(path_labels).convert(self.mode_color_label)

        if self.transform_img and self.transform_label:
            torch.manual_seed(self.random_state)
            image = self.transform_img(image)
            label = self.transform_label(label)

        return {'image': image, 'label': label}


class DataCV():
    """dataset for cross-validation."""
    def __init__(self, Data_images: List[Path], Data_labels: List[Path], num_workers: int = 2, batch_size: int = 2, n_splits: int = 5):
        super().__init__()
        self.Data_images = Data_images
        self.Data_labels = Data_labels
        self.num_workers = num_workers
        self.batch_size = batch_size

        # Cross-validation
        self.n_splits = n_splits

        # Data normalization
        self._mean = [0.3, 0.3, 0.3] # mean=[0.3, 0.3, 0.3], std=[0.09, 0.09, 0.09]
        self._std = [0.09, 0.09, 0.09]

    @property
    def normalize_transform(self):
        return v2.Normalize(mean=self._mean, std=self._std)

    @property
    def DataSet_transform(self): ## It can be train and valid dataset.
        return v2.Compose([
            v2.ToImage(),  # Convert to tensor, only needed if you had a PIL image
            v2.ToDtype(torch.uint8, scale=True),  # optional, most input are already uint8 at this
            v2.Resize(size=(512, 1536), antialias=True), # (496, 1536)
            v2.ToDtype(torch.float32, scale=True),  # Normalize expects float input
            self.normalize_transform,
            ])

    @property
    def label_transform(self):
        return v2.Compose([
            v2.ToImage(),  # Convert to tensor, only needed if you had a PIL image
            v2.ToDtype(torch.uint8, scale=True),  # optional, most input are already uint8 at this
            v2.Resize(size=(512, 1536), antialias=True), # (496, 1536)
            v2.ToDtype(torch.float32, scale=True),  # Normalize expects float input
            v2.Grayscale(),
            ])

    def get_splits(self):
        cv_ = KFold(n_splits=self.n_splits, shuffle=True, random_state = 123)

        if len(self.Data_images) == len(self.Data_labels):
            n_samples = len(self.Data_images)
        else:
            raise RuntimeError('The length of the data and label are not the same.')

        dataset_img, dataset_labels = [self.Data_images, self.Data_labels]

        for train_idx, val_idx in cv_.split(X=range(n_samples)):

            ## Train: Data and labels
            _train_img = Subset(dataset_img, train_idx)
            _train_labels = Subset(dataset_labels, train_idx)
            self._update_mean_std(dataset_img = _train_img, dataset_labels = _train_labels)
            train_dataset = _WrappedDataset(paths_img = _train_img, paths_labels = _train_labels, transform_img = self.DataSet_transform, transform_label = self.label_transform)
            train_loader = DataLoader(dataset=train_dataset, batch_size=self.batch_size, shuffle=True, num_workers=self.num_workers)

            ## Valid: Data and labels
            _val_img = Subset(dataset_img, val_idx)
            _val_labels = Subset(dataset_labels, val_idx)
            val_dataset = _WrappedDataset(paths_img = _val_img, paths_labels = _val_labels, transform_img = self.DataSet_transform, transform_label = self.label_transform)
            val_loader = DataLoader(dataset=val_dataset, batch_size=self.batch_size, shuffle=False, num_workers=self.num_workers)

            yield train_loader, val_loader

    def _update_mean_std(self, dataset_img, dataset_labels):
        """Computes the mean and std of the given (image) dataset.

        Instantiates a dataloader to compute the mean and std from batches.
        """
        UpdateMeanStd = v2.Compose([
            v2.ToImage(),  # Convert to tensor, only needed if you had a PIL image
            v2.ToDtype(torch.uint8, scale=True),  # optional, most input are already uint8 at this
            v2.Resize(size=(512, 1536), antialias=True), # (496, 1536)
            v2.ToDtype(torch.float32, scale=True),  # Normalize expects float input
            ])

        _dataset = _WrappedDataset(paths_img = dataset_img, paths_labels = dataset_labels,  transform_img = UpdateMeanStd, transform_label = UpdateMeanStd )

        _dataloader = DataLoader(dataset=_dataset, batch_size=self.batch_size, shuffle=False, num_workers=self.num_workers)

        mean, std, n_samples = 0., 0., 0.
        for dataloader_item in _dataloader:
            images = dataloader_item['image']
            batch_samples = images.size(0)
            data = images.view(batch_samples, images.size(1), -1)
            mean += data.mean(2).sum(0)
            std += data.std(2).sum(0)
            n_samples += batch_samples
        self._mean = mean / n_samples
        self._std = std / n_samples

class CV:
    """Cross-validation with a LightningModule."""
    def __init__(self, *trainer_args, **trainer_kwargs):
        super().__init__()
        self.trainer_args = trainer_args
        self.trainer_kwargs = trainer_kwargs

    def fit(self, model: LightningModule, data: DataCV):
        splits = data.get_splits()

        for fold_idx, loaders in enumerate(splits):

            tb_logger = TensorBoardLogger(save_dir='/content/lightning_logs', name = f'CV_{fold_idx + 1}')
            # checkpoint_callback0 = ModelCheckpoint(dirpath = tb_logger.log_dir, filename= "{epoch}-{loss/valid:.2f}", monitor = 'Loss', mode = 'max', save_top_k=3)
            checkpoint_callback = ModelCheckpoint(dirpath = tb_logger.log_dir,
                                                  filename= "{epoch}-{valid_data_iou/valid:.2f}",
                                                  monitor = 'valid_data_iou', mode = 'max', save_top_k= 1 ) #max_epochs

            # Clone model & instantiate a new trainer:
            _model = deepcopy(model)
            trainer = Trainer(*self.trainer_args, **self.trainer_kwargs, logger=tb_logger, callbacks = [checkpoint_callback])

            # Fit:
            trainer.fit(_model, *loaders)

class LightningModel(pl.LightningModule):
      def __init__(self, model_name, model_params, optimizer_name, optimizer_hparams, threshold_prob):
          """LightningModel.
          Args:
              model_name: Name of the model/CNN to run. Used for creating the model (see function below)
              model_params: Hyperparameters for the model, as dictionary.
              optimizer_name: Name of the optimizer to use. Currently supported: Adam, SGD
              optimizer_hparams: Hyperparameters for the optimizer, as dictionary. This includes learning rate, weight decay, etc.
            """
          super().__init__()
          self.save_hyperparameters(ignore="model")  # this line allows to access init params with 'self.hparams' attribute
          self.threshold_prob = threshold_prob
          # archs (model_name) = [ Unet, UnetPlusPlus, MAnet, Linknet, FPN, PSPNet, DeepLabV3, DeepLabV3Plus, PAN,]
          # model_params = {encoder_name: str = "resnet34", encoder_weights: _Optional[str] = "imagenet", in_channels: int = 3, classes: int = 1, **kwargs}
          self.model = smp.create_model(model_name, **model_params)

          # Create loss module
          self.loss_module = smp.losses.DiceLoss(smp.losses.BINARY_MODE, from_logits=True)

          # preprocessing parameteres for image
          # Input: encoder_name, pretrained="imagenet"
          # Output: input_space, input_range, mean, std
          params = smp.encoders.get_preprocessing_params(model_params['encoder_name'])
          self.register_buffer("std", torch.tensor(params["std"]).view(1, 3, 1, 1))
          self.register_buffer("mean", torch.tensor(params["mean"]).view(1, 3, 1, 1))

          ### metrics will be added during processing of running
          stages = ('train','valid','test',)
          self.outputs = { stage:[] for stage in stages}

      def forward(self, image):
        # Forward function that is run when visualizing the graph
        # normalize image
        image = (image - self.mean) / self.std
        return self.model(image)

      def configure_optimizers(self):
          # We will support Adam or SGD as optimizers.
          if self.hparams.optimizer_name == "Adam":
              optimizer = optim.AdamW(self.parameters(), **self.hparams.optimizer_hparams)
          elif self.hparams.optimizer_name == "SGD":
              optimizer = optim.SGD(self.parameters(), **self.hparams.optimizer_hparams)
          else:
              assert False, f'Unknown optimizer: "{self.hparams.optimizer_name}"'

          # scheduler = torch.optim.swa_utils.SWALR(optimizer, anneal_strategy="cos", anneal_epochs=3, swa_lr=0.002)
          return [optimizer] , [] #, [scheduler]

      def shared_step(self, batch, stage):
          image = batch["image"]
          labels = batch["label"]

          assert labels.ndim == 4 # Shape of the labels should be [batch_size, num_classes, height, width]
          assert labels.max() <= 1.0 and labels.min() >= 0 # Check that labels values in between 0 and 1, NOT 0 and 255 for binary segmentation

          preds = self.forward(image)
          loss = self.loss_module(preds, labels)

          # Predicted labels contains logits, and loss_fn param `from_logits` is set to True
          prob_preds = preds.sigmoid()
          labels_preds = (prob_preds > self.threshold_prob).float()

          tp, fp, fn, tn = smp.metrics.get_stats(labels_preds.long(), labels.long(), mode="binary")
          ret = {"loss": loss, "tp": tp, "fp": fp, "fn": fn, "tn": tn}

          self.outputs[stage].append(ret)
          return loss

      def shared_epoch_end(self, stage, on_step = False, on_epoch = True):
          # aggregate step metics
          loss = torch.cat([x["loss"].reshape(1) for x in self.outputs[stage]]).mean() # concatenar tensor
          tp = torch.cat([x["tp"] for x in self.outputs[stage]]) # concatenar tensor
          fp = torch.cat([x["fp"] for x in self.outputs[stage]])
          fn = torch.cat([x["fn"] for x in self.outputs[stage]])
          tn = torch.cat([x["tn"] for x in self.outputs[stage]])

          per_image_iou = smp.metrics.iou_score(tp, fp, fn, tn, reduction="micro-imagewise") # per image IoU means that we first calculate IoU score for each image
          dataset_iou = smp.metrics.iou_score(tp, fp, fn, tn, reduction="micro") # and then compute mean over these scores
          metrics = {"Loss": loss, f"{stage}_per_image_iou": per_image_iou, f"{stage}_data_iou": dataset_iou}
          print(metrics)
          self.log_dict({**metrics}, on_step=on_step, on_epoch=on_epoch, prog_bar=True, logger=True)
          self.outputs[stage].clear()

      def training_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
          return self.shared_step(batch,"train")

      def on_training_epoch_end(self):
          return self.shared_epoch_end("train", on_step = True, on_epoch = True)

      def validation_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
          return self.shared_step(batch,"valid")

      def on_validation_epoch_end(self):
          return self.shared_epoch_end("valid")

      def test_step(self, batch, batch_idx):
          return self.shared_step(batch, "test")

      def on_test_epoch_end(self):
          return self.shared_epoch_end("test")

data_transform = v2.Compose([
    v2.ToImage(),  # Convert to tensor, only needed if you had a PIL image
    v2.ToDtype(torch.uint8, scale=True),  # optional, most input are already uint8 at this
    v2.Resize(size=(512, 1536), antialias=True), # (496, 1536)
    v2.ToDtype(torch.float32, scale=True),  # Normalize expects float input
    # v2.Normalize(mean=[0.3, 0.3, 0.3], std=[0.09, 0.09, 0.09]) # we will use the same mean and var for each channel because it is gray image even though there are three channel
])

label_transform = v2.Compose([
    v2.ToImage(),  # Convert to tensor, only needed if you had a PIL image
    v2.ToDtype(torch.uint8, scale=True),  # optional, most input are already uint8 at this
    v2.Resize(size=(512, 1536), antialias=True), # (496, 1536)
    v2.ToDtype(torch.float32, scale=True),  # Normalize expects float input
    v2.Grayscale(),
])


def show_random_images(data):
    n = data.__len__()
    random_image_idx = np.random.choice(np.arange(n))
    data_ = data[random_image_idx]
    image = data_['image']
    label = data_['label']

    if isinstance(image, torch.Tensor):
        image = image.numpy().transpose(1, 2, 0)
        label = label.numpy().transpose(1, 2, 0)
        # print(np.min(label), np.max(label))

    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
    ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    ax1.imshow(np.clip(image, 0, 1) )
    ax1.set_title("Image")
    ax1.axis('off')
    ax2 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    ax2.imshow( np.clip(label, 0, 1)  , cmap = 'gray')
    ax2.set_title("Label")
    ax2.axis('off')
